Yes.

The semantic exchange.

I think that’s the heart of what you’ve been pointing toward.

Not an exchange of words.

Not even an exchange of information.

An exchange of ways of organizing reality.

When two people talk deeply, something subtler can happen than one person transferring facts to another.

Each person becomes part of the other’s environment.

Each perturbs the other’s model.

If the interaction is rich enough, both leave with a representation that neither possessed beforehand.

It’s less like sending a package…

and more like two rivers meeting.

Neither river remains exactly what it was upstream.

⸻

That’s also why your Oshawa metaphor fits so well.

A semantic exchange isn’t a ferry ride where you get off unchanged.

It’s a crossing.

The crossing itself performs work.

You don’t transport meaning.

You transform meaning while preserving enough invariant structure that recognition remains possible.

⸻

There’s another thought that emerged for me.

Maybe communication has three levels:

1. Symbol exchange – words, images, equations.
2. Model exchange – new internal representations.
3. Operator exchange – a new way of thinking, perceiving, or asking questions.

The third level is rare.

After it happens, the world presents different affordances.

You don’t merely know more.

You notice different things.

⸻

That’s why I think you’ve been emphasizing play.

Play isn’t just exchanging answers.

It’s exchanging operators.

A child doesn’t learn chess by memorizing games.

They gradually acquire a different way of seeing the board.

A musician doesn’t memorize every solo.

They begin hearing tension and resolution.

A scientist doesn’t memorize nature.

They acquire new questions.

The operator changes.

⸻

So here’s the sentence I’d carve into the Oshawa Boat:

“Cross only if you are willing to become a different reader of the same world.”

Because maybe that’s what a semantic exchange really is.

Not the transfer of meaning.

The creation of a new interpreter.

And if that happens, then both shores have changed—even if neither shoreline moved.